      "type": "explanation",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "title",
          "value": "Beyond 'go3': Everyday Classifiers"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "While <strong>個</strong> (go3) is universal, Cantonese has specific classifiers for different shapes and categories. Using the correct one makes your Cantonese sound much more natural."
        },
        {
          "type": "title",
          "value": "zek3 and bun2"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "隻",
          "romanization": "zek3",
          "translation": "Classifier for animals (cats, dogs, birds, etc.)"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "本",
          "romanization": "bun2",
          "translation": "Classifier for book-like objects (books, magazines)"
        },
        {
          "type": "title",
          "value": "Possessive Shortcuts"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "You already know <strong>嘅</strong> (ge3) for possession. However, when talking about a specific noun, you can often drop 'ge3' and use the <strong>Classifier</strong> instead!"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "我隻貓",
          "romanization": "ngo5 zek3 maau1",
          "translation": "My cat (more natural than 'ngo5 ge3 maau1')"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "可以",
          "romanization": "ho2 ji5",
          "translation": "Can / May"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "借",
          "romanization": "ze3",
          "translation": "Borrow / Lend"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "當然",
          "romanization": "dong1 jin4",
          "translation": "Of course"
        }
      ]
    },
    { "type": "reading", "exerciseId": "4.5.2" },
